<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="43">
The collections of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2492" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nomamyrmex</taxonomicName>
that I have examined from Paraguay fall neatly into two species corresponding most commonly to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32890" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">N. esenbeckii</taxonomicName>
and more rarely to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32891" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex hartigii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartigii">N. hartigii</taxonomicName>
. Watkins (1976) and Borgmeier (1955) provide characters to separate the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="43">
In contrast, literature records of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2492" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nomamyrmex</taxonomicName>
from Paraguay pertain to three forms, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32891" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex hartigii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartigii">N. hartigii</taxonomicName>
(Borgmeier 1955, Santschi 1916), 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32890" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">N. esenbeckii</taxonomicName>
(Borgmeier 1955, Santschi 1929a), and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:150748" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii crassicornis (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="esenbeckii" subSpecies="crassicornis">N. esenbeckii crassicornis</taxonomicName>
(Forel 1906, Forel 1908b, Forel 1909). The literature records of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:150748" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii crassicornis (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="esenbeckii" subSpecies="crassicornis">N. esenbeckii crassicornis</taxonomicName>
, a subspecies generally known from the more tropical regions of South America, are based on Forel’s identifications. Thus, the presence of three forms in the literature is likely an artifact of differing conceptions on the part of earlier taxonomists. Regardless of these conceptual differences, the subspecies of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32890" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">N. esenbeckii</taxonomicName>
are largely allopatric across the Neotropics (Watkins 1976). Gordon Snelling, who has examined material from throughout the region, provides a detailed case for the synonymy of all of them at www.armyants.org. I concur with Snelling’s reasoning and synonymize 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239841" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex crassicornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">N. crassicornis</taxonomicName>
under 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32890" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nomamyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nomamyrmex esenbeckii (Westwood)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esenbeckii">N. esenbeckii</taxonomicName>
here.
</paragraph>
